–1512":"1442–1512","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1395–1479":"1395–1479","14 July 1445":"14 July 1445","1395":"1395","1493":"1493","Abt 1433":"about 1433","1470":"1470","1437":"1437","1415":"1415","1479":"1479","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1411":"1411","about 1437":"about 1437","1433":"1433","1442":"1442","Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Cockpool, Dumfries-shire, , Scotland":"Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Erskine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Erskine in Renfrewshire, first recorded in 1226 in the form <i>Erskyn</i>.","History: A family of this name have held a number of Scottish titles, including the earldoms of Mar, Buchan, Kellie, and Rosslyn."],"variants":[{"name":"Erskin","meanings":["Scottish (central Scotland and Fife): variant of   Erskine  . This form of the surname is now more common in the US."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Erskine was born in 1411, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Erskine, was 17 and her mother, Lady Margaret Seton, was 17. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Charles Karel Murray. She died on 14 July 1445, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1411–14 July 1445":"1411–14. juuli 1445","1411–1445":"1411–1445","1415–1470":"1415–1470","1433–1493":"1433–1493","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1442–1512":"1442–1512